Note:
TUPLE - Heterogeneous Fixed-Arity Tuple Primitive (Tier 0)

This file implements Tuple2 through Tuple8, fixed-arity heterogeneous
record types where each slot stores a pointer-sized value (Integer / pointer).
The runtime representation is uniform: a header word that records the arity
followed by N consecutive 8-byte slots.

Architecture:
- Single concrete struct shape: { arity:u64, slot_0:u64, slot_1:u64, ... }
- Total bytes: 8 + (arity * 8)
- Maximum arity: 8 (covers Tuple2..Tuple8 in the public API)
- Slot access uses computed offsets: 8 + (index * 8)
- No tagged unions: each slot is treated as Integer-or-pointer by callers
- Comparison: element-wise equality with arity-mismatch returning 0
- Hash combiner: FNV-1a 64-bit blend over arity and every slot

Memory layout (arity=N, total = 8 + 8N bytes):
  offset 0  : arity (u64)
  offset 8  : slot 0
  offset 16 : slot 1
  ...
  offset 8 + 8 * (N-1) : slot N-1

Use cases:
- Multiple return values (proc returning a Tuple2 of (status, value))
- Heterogeneous map entries before generic type erasure
- Coordinate triples, RGB tuples, time/date tuples
- Compile-time decomposition targets for pattern matching
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

Let TUPLE_HEADER_SIZE be 8
Let TUPLE_SLOT_SIZE be 8
Let TUPLE_MAX_ARITY be 8

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TUPLE CREATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Allocate a tuple of arity 2. Arity is stored verbatim so consumers can
validate the shape before dereferencing slot offsets, which means
heterogeneous code paths cannot accidentally read past the end of the
record. The two values are written via memory_set_int64 to keep the
representation uniform with all larger arities.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Total size = 8 (header) + 2 * 8 = 24 bytes. The first qword stores arity,
the next two qwords store v0 and v1 respectively. Allocation failure
returns 0 so callers can short-circuit before consuming the value.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: O(1) - exactly 24 bytes per Tuple2 instance.
Allocation calls into the owned-heap tier (Layout.allocate); freelist
fast path makes this effectively a bump-pointer in the common case.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Slots are opaque words. The caller is responsible for distinguishing
"pointer" from "integer" semantics. No validation is performed because
v0 and v1 are pointer-sized values that the type system has already
checked at the call site.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "tuple2_create" takes v0 as Integer, v1 as Integer returns Integer:
    Let total_size be TUPLE_HEADER_SIZE plus (2 multiplied by TUPLE_SLOT_SIZE)
    Let tup be proc allocate from Layout with total_size
    If tup is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 0, 2
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 8, v0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 16, v1
    Return tup
End Process

@Reasoning
Tuple3 mirrors Tuple2 with a third slot. The uniform layout is the
critical invariant: every tuple_get_N accessor below assumes the
header-plus-slot ordering, so deviation here would silently corrupt
all higher-arity readers.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Total size = 8 + 3 * 8 = 32 bytes. Slots stored at offsets 8, 16, 24.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: O(1) - 32 bytes.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Opaque words; semantics determined by the call site.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "tuple3_create" takes v0 as Integer, v1 as Integer, v2 as Integer returns Integer:
    Let total_size be TUPLE_HEADER_SIZE plus (3 multiplied by TUPLE_SLOT_SIZE)
    Let tup be proc allocate from Layout with total_size
    If tup is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 0, 3
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 8, v0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 16, v1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 24, v2
    Return tup
End Process

@Reasoning
Tuple4 used for RGBA / quaternion / 4-vector style records. Extending
the layout one slot at a time avoids any variable-arity branching.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Total size = 8 + 4 * 8 = 40 bytes. Slots at offsets 8, 16, 24, 32.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: O(1) - 40 bytes.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Opaque words.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "tuple4_create" takes v0 as Integer, v1 as Integer, v2 as Integer, v3 as Integer returns Integer:
    Let total_size be TUPLE_HEADER_SIZE plus (4 multiplied by TUPLE_SLOT_SIZE)
    Let tup be proc allocate from Layout with total_size
    If tup is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 0, 4
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 8, v0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 16, v1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 24, v2
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 32, v3
    Return tup
End Process

@Reasoning
Tuple5 widens the layout one slot at a time so a single linear walk
in tuple_equal / tuple_hash can iterate arity slots without arity-
specific code.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Total size = 8 + 5 * 8 = 48 bytes. Slots at offsets 8..40 step 8.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: O(1) - 48 bytes.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Opaque words.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "tuple5_create" takes v0 as Integer, v1 as Integer, v2 as Integer, v3 as Integer, v4 as Integer returns Integer:
    Let total_size be TUPLE_HEADER_SIZE plus (5 multiplied by TUPLE_SLOT_SIZE)
    Let tup be proc allocate from Layout with total_size
    If tup is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 0, 5
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 8, v0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 16, v1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 24, v2
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 32, v3
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 40, v4
    Return tup
End Process

@Reasoning
Tuple6 widens the layout further. Beyond arity 6, prefer struct types,
but Tuple6/7/8 stay first-class for cases like (line, col, fname, len,
kind, flags) lexer records.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Total size = 8 + 6 * 8 = 56 bytes. Slots at offsets 8..48 step 8.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: O(1) - 56 bytes.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Opaque words.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "tuple6_create" takes v0 as Integer, v1 as Integer, v2 as Integer, v3 as Integer, v4 as Integer, v5 as Integer returns Integer:
    Let total_size be TUPLE_HEADER_SIZE plus (6 multiplied by TUPLE_SLOT_SIZE)
    Let tup be proc allocate from Layout with total_size
    If tup is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 0, 6
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 8, v0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 16, v1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 24, v2
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 32, v3
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 40, v4
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 48, v5
    Return tup
End Process

@Reasoning
Tuple7 is rare in human code but appears in cross-process IPC records
(seven fields of a syscall result). Worth a first-class constructor
so callers do not stack-allocate dynamic Lists for one fixed shape.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Total size = 8 + 7 * 8 = 64 bytes. Slots at offsets 8..56 step 8.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: O(1) - 64 bytes.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Opaque words.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "tuple7_create" takes v0 as Integer, v1 as Integer, v2 as Integer, v3 as Integer, v4 as Integer, v5 as Integer, v6 as Integer returns Integer:
    Let total_size be TUPLE_HEADER_SIZE plus (7 multiplied by TUPLE_SLOT_SIZE)
    Let tup be proc allocate from Layout with total_size
    If tup is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 0, 7
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 8, v0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 16, v1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 24, v2
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 32, v3
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 40, v4
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 48, v5
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 56, v6
    Return tup
End Process

@Reasoning
Tuple8 caps the public arity ceiling at 8. Larger records should use
Type called "X" struct definitions; the ceiling keeps the constructor
table bounded and prevents accidental "tuple of 30 fields" anti-pattern.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Total size = 8 + 8 * 8 = 72 bytes. Slots at offsets 8..64 step 8.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: O(1) - 72 bytes.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Opaque words.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "tuple8_create" takes v0 as Integer, v1 as Integer, v2 as Integer, v3 as Integer, v4 as Integer, v5 as Integer, v6 as Integer, v7 as Integer returns Integer:
    Let total_size be TUPLE_HEADER_SIZE plus (8 multiplied by TUPLE_SLOT_SIZE)
    Let tup be proc allocate from Layout with total_size
    If tup is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 0, 8
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 8, v0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 16, v1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 24, v2
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 32, v3
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 40, v4
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 48, v5
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 56, v6
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, 64, v7
    Return tup
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TUPLE DESTRUCTION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
A single destroy function suffices for all arities because the
allocator (Layout.deallocate) records the size in the heap header;
slot contents are not freed because they are opaque words whose
ownership is determined by the caller, not the tuple.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Validates the pointer, then defers to Layout.deallocate. The arity
field is not consulted because the underlying allocator already knows
the block size; reading arity here would only catch corruption that
the allocator's own header check already catches.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: O(0) - returns memory to the tier-3 owned heap.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller must own the tuple; double-destroy is detected by the underlying
allocator's quarantine path when canaries are enabled.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "tuple_destroy" takes tup as Integer returns Integer:
    If tup is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc deallocate from Layout with tup
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TUPLE INSPECTION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Returns the arity stored at offset 0. Used for runtime polymorphism
when a function accepts "any tuple" and must select branches based
on arity.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Single memory_get_int64 at offset 0. Null tuple returns 0 so callers
can treat arity-zero / null uniformly.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "tuple_arity" takes tup as Integer returns Integer:
    If tup is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with tup, 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TUPLE ACCESSORS - tuple_get_N
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Indexed accessor that validates arity before reading. Returns 0 on
out-of-range to keep parity with list_get and dictionary_get error
behavior, which is what existing higher-level passes expect.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Offset = TUPLE_HEADER_SIZE + index * TUPLE_SLOT_SIZE = 8 + index * 8.
Arity check guards against accidental access into the next heap block.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Bounds-checked read. Cannot read past the allocated block.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "tuple_get" takes tup as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    If tup is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If index is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let arity be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with tup, 0
    If index is greater than or equal to arity:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let offset be TUPLE_HEADER_SIZE plus (index multiplied by TUPLE_SLOT_SIZE)
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with tup, offset
End Process

@Reasoning
Fixed-index accessor for slot 0. Generated explicitly because the
"name a tuple slot by position" convention is widespread in pattern
matching and the explicit form lets the optimizer fold the offset.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Delegates to tuple_get with index 0 to keep one source of truth for
bounds validation.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Bounds-checked read.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "tuple_get_0" takes tup as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc tuple_get with tup, 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Slot 1 accessor. Same delegation pattern.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Delegates to tuple_get with index 1.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Bounds-checked.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "tuple_get_1" takes tup as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc tuple_get with tup, 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Slot 2 accessor.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Delegates to tuple_get with index 2.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Bounds-checked.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "tuple_get_2" takes tup as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc tuple_get with tup, 2
End Process

@Reasoning
Slot 3 accessor.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Delegates to tuple_get with index 3.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Bounds-checked.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "tuple_get_3" takes tup as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc tuple_get with tup, 3
End Process

@Reasoning
Slot 4 accessor.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Delegates to tuple_get with index 4.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Bounds-checked.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "tuple_get_4" takes tup as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc tuple_get with tup, 4
End Process

@Reasoning
Slot 5 accessor.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Delegates to tuple_get with index 5.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Bounds-checked.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "tuple_get_5" takes tup as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc tuple_get with tup, 5
End Process

@Reasoning
Slot 6 accessor.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
