Note: ============================================================================
Note: TUPLE MUTATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Tuples are nominally immutable but in the compiler pipeline we
sometimes want to update one field in place rather than allocate a
fresh tuple (hot loops in MIR construction).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Bounds-checked write to the slot at offset 8 + index * 8.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller-controlled mutation. Use sparingly to keep value-semantics
invariants intact for shared tuples.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "tuple_set" takes tup as Integer, index as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    If tup is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If index is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let arity be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with tup, 0
    If index is greater than or equal to arity:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let offset be TUPLE_HEADER_SIZE plus (index multiplied by TUPLE_SLOT_SIZE)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tup, offset, value
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TUPLE COMPARISON
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Structural equality. Two tuples are equal iff they have the same arity
and every slot is bit-equal. Returns 0/1 to compose with the rest of
the comparison-primitive API.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Arity mismatch short-circuits to 0. Otherwise iterate slot-by-slot
with memory_get_int64 and compare; first mismatch returns 0.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(N) in arity. Space: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Bit-equality. Pointer slots compare by address, not by pointee.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "tuple_equal" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    If a is equal to b:
        Return 1
    End If
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let arity_a be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with a, 0
    Let arity_b be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with b, 0
    If arity_a is not equal to arity_b:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than arity_a:
        Let offset be TUPLE_HEADER_SIZE plus (i multiplied by TUPLE_SLOT_SIZE)
        Let va be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with a, offset
        Let vb be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with b, offset
        If va is not equal to vb:
            Return 0
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TUPLE HASH
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
FNV-1a 64-bit blend over the arity word followed by every slot.
Provides good avalanche for use as a Dictionary key with composite
tuple keys.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Initialize hash to FNV offset basis (14695981039346656037 mod 2^63
because Runa Integers are 63-bit signed in some lower MIRs; we mask
to a positive 63-bit hash). For each input word the algorithm folds
in 8 bytes at a time via xor + multiply by FNV prime 1099511628211.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(N) in arity. Space: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
FNV-1a is not cryptographic. Adequate for hash-table bucket selection;
unsuitable for adversarial input where collision attacks are a concern.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "tuple_hash" takes tup as Integer returns Integer:
    If tup is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let hash be 2166136261
    Let arity be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with tup, 0
    Set hash to hash bitwise xor arity
    Set hash to hash multiplied by 16777619
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than arity:
        Let offset be TUPLE_HEADER_SIZE plus (i multiplied by TUPLE_SLOT_SIZE)
        Let v be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with tup, offset
        Set hash to hash bitwise xor v
        Set hash to hash multiplied by 16777619
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    If hash is less than 0:
        Set hash to 0 minus hash
    End If
    Return hash
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TUPLE FORMAT
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Returns the total allocated byte size of a tuple. Used by serialization
layers that need to bulk-copy a tuple without dispatching on arity.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Size = TUPLE_HEADER_SIZE + arity * TUPLE_SLOT_SIZE.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "tuple_byte_size" takes tup as Integer returns Integer:
    If tup is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let arity be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with tup, 0
    Return TUPLE_HEADER_SIZE plus (arity multiplied by TUPLE_SLOT_SIZE)
End Process

@Reasoning
Allocates a fresh tuple that is a bit-for-bit copy of the input.
Useful when handing a tuple across an ownership boundary and the
receiving subsystem must not see future mutations.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Compute the byte size, allocate a new block of the same size, then
memory_copy the bytes. The copy is shallow: pointer slots still
reference the same pointees.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(N) in arity. Space: O(N).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Shallow copy. Pointee ownership is not transferred.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "tuple_clone" takes tup as Integer returns Integer:
    If tup is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let size be proc tuple_byte_size with tup
    Let copy be proc allocate from Layout with size
    If copy is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_copy from Memory with copy, tup, size
    Return copy
End Process
